{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a3d4950f-5417-4522-9ba1-af43acd7b827","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Get a shell into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Getting the file off the container\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis gives live CPU %, GC, threadpool stats — useful to confirm the problem before collecting a full trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails due to no SDK in the container image, copy the tools from the host or use a sidecar with the SDK. You can also set `DOTNET_EnableDiagnostics=1` and use `dotnet-trace` from outside the container via a diagnostic port (`DOTNET_DiagnosticPorts`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"550eab71-ab8e-4466-a68c-d8e9f561d33a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":457,"requestId":"D7EE:20D09C:B83D2A:D5AD97:69F2AF33"},"id":"5e9848bf-2561-4e3e-a23d-71c431524a8e","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:24:16.932Z","parentId":"cc57561c-dc45-4fdd-99f3-64bf6a5f3254"}
